{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is the handoff between request builder/config and API client payload. A unit test of a helper could miss wiring bugs where the built taxonomy list is dropped or partially mapped before send. Rejected System: behavior does not require real network/OS/subprocess; a stub client that captures outbound payload is sufficient. Rejected Agentic/Workflow: no dependence on model decision quality or multi-step agent loop.","test_description":"Wire classifier module with real request-construction code and a fake in-process API client that records requests. Invoke classify with a taxonomy, then assert outbound payload contains the full label set exactly once and unmodified.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.25,"Integration":0.65,"System":0.07,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Core failure is deterministic label-validation/normalization logic on one response object. No real infra or model-quality dependency is needed to surface the bug. Rejected Integration: behavior text focuses on mapping invalid label to fallback, which can be exercised directly on local function/object input.","test_description":"Call normalization/decision function with taxonomy plus raw label outside taxonomy (e.g., \"medical\"). Assert returned label is exactly \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.78,"Integration":0.2,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the sa